</blockquote>

<hr>

<h2>
<a name="subscribe">
Subscribing to Tech-talk</a></h2>

<p>
There are two ways to read to tech-talk messages:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#rss">Via RSS</a></li>
<li><a href="#email">By email</a></li>
</ul>

<h3>
<a name="rss">
RSS Subscription</a></h3>

<p>
You can be notified about the arrival of new tech-talk messages at the list
archive without having to subscribe, using the <a href="rss.xml">RSS feed
<img src="../icons/feeds.png" border="0"></a>.  Visiting that link in a regular
web browser won't show anything particularly useful; if you aren't familiar with
RSS <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSS_%28file_format%29">read this</a>. 
I use the <a href="http://reader.google.com/">Google Reader</a> for reading RSS
feeds, but there are many readers available, including one built into the
Firefox web browser and another in the Thunderbird email program.</p>

<p>
Note that the tech-talk RSS feed does not include the full text of the messages,
only the subject line and author's name, but it does provide a link to the
full message in the archive.</p>

<p>
The tech-talk list is moderated for non-members, so if you haven't subscribed
using the Mailman interface (or been grandfathered in from the previous
listserver) your messages may be held for approval before being circulated. If
you prefer to use the RSS interface but want to avoid the moderation delay you
should
<a href="https://mailman.aps.anl.gov/mailman/listinfo/tech-talk">subscribe</a>
but configure Mailman to not actually send you any messages.</p>

<h3>
<a name="email">
Email Subscription</a></h3>

<p>
To have tech-talk messages forwarded to your email inbox, visit the
<a href="https://mailman.aps.anl.gov/mailman/listinfo/tech-talk">mailman
information page</a> for the tech-talk list and fill in the subscription form
there.  You can also subscribe via email; send a message to
<a href="mailto:tech-talk-request@aps.anl.gov">tech-talk-request@aps.anl.gov</a>
that contains just the work "help" in either the subject or message body for
further instructions.</p>

<hr>
<h2>To send a message to a list</h2>

<p>
In general you should subscribe if you intend to send messages to this list
(note that you can subscribe but turn message delivery off if you normally read
tech-talk through the RSS feed). If you aren't subscribed, your message will
have to be approved by a list moderator, which will delay its delivery. However
it should eventually get through (unless it looks like spam), so a subscription
is not essential.</p>

<p>
Address messages to
<a href="mailto:tech-talk@aps.anl.gov"><tt>tech-talk@aps.anl.gov</tt></a>, for
example:</p>

<blockquote>
<table border=1 width="90%"><tr><td class="yellow">

<table width="100%">
<tr>
<td width="10%" align=right>
<b>Subject:<br>
From:<br>
To:</b></td>

<td><i>Please use a relevent subject line</i><br>
mail_address@your.site<br>
<a href="mailto:tech-talk@aps.anl.gov">tech-talk@aps.anl.gov</a><br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
&nbsp;<br>
<tt><i>Your message...</i></tt>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>

<p>
Some broken mail programs may try to send messages to the bounce-address
<tt>tech-talk-bounces@aps.anl.gov</tt> which is the envelope return address used
for all outgoing messages and is only supposed to receive information about
messages that can't be delivered. If you do not correct this address before
sending, your messages will be delayed as they will have to be forwared by the
list owner.</p>

</td></tr>

